There is a miscompilation issue report in HashRecognize: 

This program returns 0 at -O0/s and 139 at -O1/2/3

```
int a, b;
short c, e;
long d[56];
int main() {
  a = 0;
  for (; a < 6; a++) {
    b = 0;
    for (; b < 8; b++) {
      if ((e ^ c) & 32768)
        e = e << 1 ^ 3;
      else
        e <<= 1;
      c <<= 1;
    }
    d[b + c - a] = 0;
  }
}
```

Compiler Explorer: https://godbolt.org/z/fxjj1o4Yf

The maintainers proposed the following patch to fix the issue:

commit 3bc9b28fe5bc3775229ceb6e498747970606d7d5
Author: Ramkumar Ramachandra <ramkumar.ramachandra@codasip.com>
Date:   Wed Oct 29 21:50:12 2025 +0000

    [HashRecognize] Forbid optz when data.next has exit-block user (#165574)

    The CRC optimization relies on stripping the auxiliary data completely,
    and should hence be forbidden when it has a user in the exit-block.
    Forbid this case, fixing a miscompile.

    Fixes #165382.

diff --git a/llvm/lib/Analysis/HashRecognize.cpp b/llvm/lib/Analysis/HashRecognize.cpp
index 4529123508a7..8974ce5734b1 100644
--- a/llvm/lib/Analysis/HashRecognize.cpp
+++ b/llvm/lib/Analysis/HashRecognize.cpp
@@ -468,8 +468,11 @@ std::variant<PolynomialInfo, StringRef> HashRecognize::recognizeCRC() const {

     // Ensure that the PHIs have exactly two uses:
     // the bit-shift, and the XOR (or a cast feeding into the XOR).
+    // Also ensure that the SimpleRecurrence's evolution doesn't have stray
+    // users.
     if (!ConditionalRecurrence.Phi->hasNUses(2) ||
-        !SimpleRecurrence.Phi->hasNUses(2))
+        !SimpleRecurrence.Phi->hasNUses(2) ||
+        SimpleRecurrence.BO->getUniqueUndroppableUser() != SimpleRecurrence.Phi)
       return "Recurrences have stray uses";

     // Check that the SelectInst ConditionalRecurrence.Step is conditional on


